SIMPLE: protestation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Protestation
<hw>Prot`es*ta"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>protestatio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>protestation</ets>. See
<er>Protest</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of making a protest; a
public avowal; a solemn declaration, especially of dissent.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧ The <xex>protestation</xex> of our faith.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Latimer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>Formerly, a declaration in
common-law pleading, by which the party interposes an oblique allegation
or denial of some fact, protesting that it does or does not exist, and
at the same time avoiding a direct affirmation or denial.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Protestator</ent>⟦br⟧
